Idea: **Title:** Conditional Scattering-Flow Manifold (CSFM) for Robust OoD Detection

To isolate the subtle non-Gaussian baryonic feedback signal, we will implement a two-stage pipeline: feature extraction via a 2D Wavelet Scattering Transform (WST) and density estimation using a Conditional Normalizing Flow. First, we map each reconstructed 2D convergence map into a compressed latent space of scattering coefficients (orders $j=0, 1, 2$) using `kymatio`, which explicitly captures the high-order moments and peak-void morphologies characteristic of baryonic feedback while discarding low-information Gaussian noise. We then train a Masked Autoregressive Flow (MAF) from the `zuko` library, conditioned on the five cosmological and nuisance parameters $(\Omega_m, S_8, T_{AGN}, f_0, \Delta z)$, to learn the conditional density $p(\text{features} | \theta)$. By training on 25,856 augmented noisy maps, the flow learns to marginalize over the nuisance parameter space effectively. The final OoD score for each test sample is the negative log-likelihood $-\log p(\text{features} | \theta_{\text{map}})$, where $\theta_{\text{map}}$ is estimated via a rapid pre-trained ResNet-18 regressor. This architecture compresses the 132,019-dimensional input into a robust, low-dimensional representation that focuses exclusively on the scales ($1-10$ arcmin) where inter-code hydrodynamical differences manifest, ensuring convergence within the 15-minute training limit.


Iteration 1:
Idea: **Title:** Hierarchical Scattering-Flow Density Estimation for Marginalized OoD Detection

To isolate baryonic feedback signatures while marginalizing over nuisance parameters, we will implement a deep density estimator using a Masked Autoregressive Flow (MAF) trained directly on Wavelet Scattering Transform (WST) coefficients. We compute the WST on reconstructed 2D maps using `kymatio` to extract high-order, scale-specific features (orders 1-2, scales 1–10 arcmin) that are sensitive to non-Gaussian baryonic feedback while remaining robust to Gaussian noise. The MAF is trained on the entire training set of 25,856 noisy realizations; by incorporating the 5 known parameters ($\Omega_m, S_8, T_{AGN}, f_0, \Delta z$) as conditional inputs during training, the model learns the joint density $p(\text{features}, \theta)$. For test maps where labels are unknown, we assign the OoD score by marginalizing the conditional density over the prior parameter distribution, $p(\text{features}) = \int p(\text{features} | \theta) p(\theta) d\theta$, approximated via Monte Carlo sampling. This approach avoids explicit parameter estimation for test samples, instead evaluating the likelihood of the observed features under the aggregated distribution of all valid hydrodynamical realizations. The resulting negative log-likelihood provides a robust, non-parametric metric that naturally flags samples inconsistent with the learned baryonic physics manifold, effectively ignoring nuisance-driven variance.
    

